Also funny thing is that we are not talking about any perpetual ownership. The blockchain stores only a link, which can disappear or change.

Petra National Park Structures — Carved By Hand or Laser? Notice the large amount of cubic feet cut out on the border of the structure, as if a large laser was set to cut from a certain 3D file that includes the empty space around the structure layer of the file. That would explain why it is a perfect rectangle cut out, even the corners on top are cut out as well. If this was hand-carved, time would not be spent attempting to carve out extra space that isn't even connected to the structure at all. Furthermore, notice how smooth and sharp the cut is on the left side. It's almost like someone cut through the rock with a hot knife. That alone dissuades me from believing that this was hand-carved.

Terrible Architectural "Improvements" |Kluczynski Federal Building The first photo is of the Chicago Federal Building, erected in 1905. This building was demolished in 1965 to make way for the Kluczynski Federal Building, pictured in the second photo. Apparently the original building was "not up to code." But look at what replaced it. The mere fact that it is an eye-sore should render the new one not up to code. The thing looks like the inside of a PC.

Structure Petrification — Link Is it me, or does this structure look like it is becoming part of the rock? In the second 2 images we find a partly petrified WWII triangulation station... Perched on the eroding seaside bluffs near Devil's Slide, these hardened pill-boxes were a triangulation station and observation site used during World War II as part of the harbor defense of San Francisco. Prior to the advent of radar, military personnel would use binoculars and compasses to search for ships at sea and relay their coordinates to a central post. By combining information from multiple observation posts, a ship's precise location could be determined by triangulation. Link If a building can naturally (or unnaturally) become apart of the rock it sits on, what does that say about the mountains we observe?

The Faraday Cage The Faraday cage is a electrical phenomenon of conductors discovered by Michael Faraday in 1836. It is a property of an enclosed conductor that says that if the conductor is placed in an electric field, charges will be distributed along the outside of that conductor that will in effect create an opposing field within the conductor that cancels the external field leaving the inside of the conductor empty of any electrical field. As you can see from the animated picture below, first the enclosed conductor is introduced to an electric field. Charge separation then begins within the conductor. As charges accumulate on opposite sides of the conductor, a new field 180 degrees off the external field is generated within the conductor that cancels the external field leaving the potential within the cage at 0. @canadiancuriosities

url_description: The manticore or mantichore (Latin: mantichora; reconstructed Old Persian: *martyahvārah; Modern Persian: مردخوار mard-khar) is a legendary creature from ancient Persian mythology, similar to the Egyptian sphinx that proliferated in Western European medieval art as well. It has the head of a human, the body of a lion, and the tail of a scorpion or a tail covered in venomous spines similar to porcupine quills. There are some accounts that the spines can be launched like arrows. It eats its victims whole, using its three rows of teeth, and leaves no bones behind.

ARTICLE XI. Of the Rhinoceros. THe Rhinoceros borrows his name from the horn in his snout.* Some call him an Aegyptian Ox, some an Aethio∣pian Bull, but they mistake; for there are none in Aegypt, except by chance. In Aethiopia indeed is a bull like him in the horn, which the unskilfull miscall a Rhinoceros. Authours are most uncertain in their de∣scription of him. Pliny in short thus;*That hee hath one horn in his Nose, he is as tall as the Elephant, his thighs much shorter, box-coloured. Others add, that he hath a swines-head,* an oxes-tayl, the Ele∣phants hew; his horn is two foot long, that he is in the Province of Mangus; that he is cold of temper; the horn on the tip of his snowt is sharp, strong as iron, his skin so tough, that no dart can pierce it; that he hath another shorter horn on his right shoulder. Some say, two in his nose, others say, one in his forehead. Some make the horn strait, like a Trumpet, with a black crosse streaked.* Some say it is crooked; some flat;* some, turning up. Some write that he hath two girdles on his back curling, and winding like those of Dragons; one turning toward his mane;* the other toward his loyns. But Bontius, who hath seen the Rhinoceros a hundred times, both kept in Den, and loose in woods,* writes that his skin is ash-coloured like the Elephants, very rugged, full of deep folds on the sides, and back, thick of hide, that a Japons sword cannot enter; the folds are like shields, or shells. He is hog-snouted, but not so blunt-nosed, their horn at the end is different according to their age: in some ash-coloured, sometimes black, sometimes white, he is not so long-legged, nor sightly as the Elephant. He is found in the deserts of Africa,* in Aba∣sia, in many parts of Asia, in Bengala, and Ja∣catra; Not knowen to the Greeks in Aristo∣teles time; nor to the Romans afore the year DCLXVI after the building of Rome. Some say Augustus shewed on in a Triumph. Some,* that Pompey was the first, who pre∣sented him in his Palays. He hath a rough tongue, and feeds on grasse, and briars. He holds enmity with the Elephant. He hurts not mankind, unlesse provoked. When he is to fight,* he sharpens his horn on the stones: In combate, he aimes at the belly, which he knows to be soft; out of which he lets all his enemies blood. If he cannot come at the belly, the Elephant with his trunk and teeth dispatcheth him. Provoked, he makes no more of a Man and an Horse, then of a flea; he can with his sharp tongue lick a man to death; fetching of skin and flesh to the bare bones. Shoot him, and he with a hideous cry layes all flat, that comes in his way, even the thickest trees. Read stories of his fiercenes in Bontius. Hee delights strangely in mud. Being to fight, shee secures her yong one first: Hee grunts like a hog. The Moors feed on his flesh, which is so sinewy, that they had need of iron teeth to chaw it. The skin steeped in wine is given in against ma∣lignant feavers.* The horne some prescribe against poyson. The dainty ones among the Romans used it in bathing for a cruize; They kept oyl in it for them that bathed: I cannot say there are different kinds of these beasts. Yet they say, there was one taken in Africa as great as a wild Asse, the horn two cubits long, the feet like the Deers, eared like the Horse, tayled like the Ox.

Giving a short lesson on Telegram bots for those afraid that they can get you doxed. So when you put a bot in your group and it has access to messages, the owner of the bot (the one with the bot token) can use the requests library to retrieve the data of incoming posts. Below is an example. {'ok': True, 'result': [{'update_id': 444402537, 'message': {'message_id': 35328, 'from': {'id': 1087968824, 'is_bot': True, 'first_name': 'Group', 'username': 'GroupAnonymousBot'}, 'author_signature': 'Admin', 'sender_chat': {'id': -1001184687537, 'title': 'HTGR Group', 'type': 'supergroup'}, 'chat': {'id': -1001184687537, 'title': 'HTGR Group', 'type': 'supergroup'}, 'date': 1687945912, 'text': 'test'}}]} None of the above data will get you doxed. However, the bot is able to retrieve the media of posts. Here is what that looks like. {'ok': True, 'result': [{'update_id': 444402563, 'message': {'message_id': 35339, 'from': {'id': 1087968824, 'is_bot': True, 'first_name': 'Group', 'username': 'GroupAnonymousBot'}, 'author_signature': 'Admin', 'sender_chat': {'id': -1001184687537, 'title': 'HTGR Group', 'type': 'supergroup'}, 'chat': {'id': -1001184687537, 'title': 'HTGR Group', 'type': 'supergroup'}, 'date': 1687946969, 'photo': [{'file_id': 'AgACAgEAAx0CRpzlsQACigtknAbZVr7425j3ZtnXbx7eHaM9_gACc6sxG-EB4ER9BMVwpNysjAEAAwIAA3MAAy8E', 'file_unique_id': 'AQADc6sxG-EB4ER4', 'file_size': 1757, 'width': 59, 'height': 90}, {'file_id': 'AgACAgEAAx0CRpzlsQACigtknAbZVr7425j3ZtnXbx7eHaM9_gACc6sxG-EB4ER9BMVwpNysjAEAAwIAA20AAy8E', 'file_unique_id': 'AQADc6sxG-EB4ERy', 'file_size': 9970, 'width': 138, 'height': 212}], 'caption': 'image test'}}]} Again, none of the above will get you doxed unless you send a picture with sensitive information in the image itself like your address or your license plate. However, any and all media you send in groups can be downloaded with this post data. This includes any videos or movies you share. Despite no sensitive data being present (or visible) in Telegram messages, you still may not like the idea of bots constantly reading each and every message in a group in real time. But I would like to remind you that it is the only way for the bots to function at all. The information of the messages is required to check for spam, blacklisted words, or whatever else you use bots for. Telegram operates very discretely and that is on purpose. The whole point is to keep the information as private as possible, but that comes with a cost. Any bot you add to your group that is given permission to read messages has the full ability to scrape these incoming messages and log them away in a database with virtually zero trace. The post here suggests that the Group Help bot has been scraping messages this whole time, as that may be the only way that something like this could have happened. I would also like to note that it is highly unlikely that the bot would have been able to provide the Italian government with private payment information unless some retards in the group stupidly sent it in the group itself, which isn't a probable theory. In conclusion, bots aren't that bad. Yes, they have the ability to scrape your messages, but the data they are scraping is next to nothing. In fact, if a fed wanted your message data, he would use a userbot instead. A userbot is way better than a regular bot because it is hooked up to a user account instead of a dedicated bot account. What this means is that a fed could join your group with a regular old account, say nothing at all, and quietly scrape all of the group's messages in real time and you'd never know. The glown*ggers will probably be able to timezone dox you if they're smart, but they aren't going to actually be able to dox you unless you're being stupid.

url_title: Mozart - Symphony No. 40 in G minor, K. 550 [complete]
url_description: Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart wrote his Symphony No. 40 in G minor, KV. 550, in 1788. It is sometimes referred to as the "Great G minor symphony," to distinguish it from the "Little G minor symphony," No. 25. The two are the only minor key symphonies Mozart wrote. The 40th Symphony was completed on 25 July 1788. The composition occupied an exceptionally productive period of just a few weeks in 1788, during which time he also completed the 39th and 41st symphonies (26 June and 10 August, respectively). The symphony is scored (in its revised version) for flute, 2 oboes, 2 clarinets, 2 bassoons, 2 horns, and strings. Notably missing are trumpets and timpani. The work is in four movements, in the usual arrangement (fast movement, slow movement, minuet, fast movement) for a classical-style symphony: 1. Molto allegro, 2/2 2. Andante, 6/8 3. Menuetto. Allegretto -- Trio, 3/4 4. Finale. Allegro assai, 2/2. Every movement but the third is in sonata form; the minuet and trio are in the usual ternary form. This work has elicited varying interpretations from critics. Robert Schumann regarded it as possessing "Grecian lightness and grace". Donald Francis Tovey saw in it the character of opera buffa. Almost certainly, however, the most common perception today is that the symphony is tragic in tone and intensely emotional; for example, Charles Rosen (in The Classical Style) has called the symphony "a work of passion, violence, and grief." Although interpretations differ, the symphony is unquestionably one of Mozart's most greatly admired works, and it is frequently performed and recorded. Ludwig van Beethoven knew the symphony well, copying out 29 measures from the score in one of his sketchbooks. It is thought that the opening theme of the last movement may have inspired Beethoven in composing the third movement of his Fifth Symphony. ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- FREE .mp3 and .wav files of all Mozart's music at: http://www.mozart-archiv.de/ FREE sheet music scores of any Mozart piece at: http://dme.mozarteum.at/DME/nma/start.php?l=2 ALSO check out these cool sites: http://musopen.org/ and http://imslp.org/wiki/ ------------------------------------------------------------------------- NOTE: I do not know who the performers of this are, nor the place and date of recording!!! Any suggestions are welcome. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ENJOY!!!! :D

Is the speed of light correct? Is there even a speed of light? https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bHIhgxav9LY With mainstream scientific assumptions, the explanation for the electricity reaching the light bulb instantly is because the wires are not actually carrying a current, but oscillating. So how do we know the speed of light? Olaus Roemer in 1676 claimed to know because he assumed Jupiter and its moon's size and location, which have never been proven. James Bradley in 1728 claimed to know because he assumed the speed of the Earth around the sun, which has never been proven or observed. Armand Fizeau's experiment in 1849 is the first that actually looks legitimate. But is speed of light travel really what is observed in this experiment? There are two interpretations for the results. The first is that light has a speed, which is very reasonable. The second is that light is instantaneous and fades in equally across the supposed current. The only part being observed is the end where the light appears in your eye. It is impossible to know which explanation is correct when only observing the results of this experiment. The light may need time to fade in when exposed to a new destination (in this case, it is behind the wheel). The guy in this video demonstrates that an electrical current powers the light bulb at the same speed no matter how long the cables are. This heavily implies that light travel is instantaneous and takes a slight amount of time to fade in, which it does equally along the entire current. The speed of light definitely seems to exist, but it is more than likely the speed of light fading in, not the speed of light traveling to its destination.

We use this tuning system today and I'll give you a few points as to why it is retarded: The perfect fifth is not perfect The major 3rd is way off The tritone is dead center between the octave They fixed every note in the chromatic scale to be at an equal distance apart from one another because it was easier, not actually better.
